73
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:48,216
two Hollywood productions released to mark the fifth anniversary of the September 11th.

74
00:06:49,640 --> 00:06:56,056
Paul Greengrass's United 93 and Oliver Stone's World Trade Center.

75
00:06:56,056 --> 00:07:02,634
The first thing that strikes the eye is that both films try to be as anti-Hollywood as possible.

76
00:07:02,634 --> 00:07:11,460
They both focus on the courage of ordinary people with no glamorous stars, no special effects, no grandiloquent heroic

77
00:07:11,801 --> 00:07:19,297
gestures, just a terse realistic depiction of ordinary people in extraordinary circumstances.

78
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:27,838
It is, however, this very touch of authenticity which raises, I think, some disturbing questions.

79
00:07:28,660 --> 00:07:34,938
The first thing one cannot but note is how both films tell the story of an exception.

80
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:45,115
United 93 is about the only one of the four kidnapped planes in which the terrorists failed, which did not hit its destination.

81
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:57,518
World Trade Center tells the story of the two of those 20 or so policemen, firemen, who were saved from the ruins of World Trade Center.

82
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:03,630
The disaster is thus turned into a kind of triumph, most notably in United 93.

83
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:10,873
Here, a comparison with Spielberg's Schindler's List is instructive.

84
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:21,879
Although I think Schindler's List is a failure, the idea to choose Schindler as a hero was a correct one.

85
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:32,737
It is precisely by focusing on a German who did something to help the Jews, that one demonstrates how it was possible to do something,

86
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:41,336
and thus to condemn those who did nothing, claiming that the regime was so totalitarian, it was not possible to do anything, and so on.

87
00:08:42,021 --> 00:08:52,796
In United 93, on the contrary, the focus on the rebellion serves the purpose of preventing us to ask the truly pertinent questions.

88
00:08:53,300 --> 00:08:56,938
That is to say, let us indulge in a simple mental experiment.

89
00:08:57,320 --> 00:09:04,437
Let us imagine both films, United 93, World Trade Center with the same change.

90
00:09:04,960 --> 00:09:06,549
Let us say that instead of United 93,

91
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:15,938
we would get a film called American 11, the name of another flight which did hit its target.

92
00:09:16,341 --> 00:09:30,516
Or let us imagine World Trade Center remade as the story of two of the firefighters or policemen who did die in the rubble of the Twin Towers after postponed prolonged suffering,

93
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:37,296
without in any way justifying the terrible crime or showing an understanding for it.

94
00:09:37,900 --> 00:09:42,888
Such aversion would confront us with the true horror of the situation.

95
00:09:44,121 --> 00:09:53,355
It would thus compel us to think, to start asking serious questions about how such a thing could have happened and what does it mean.

96
00:09:54,340 --> 00:10:07,679
The second feature, both films restrain not only from taking a political stance about the events, but even from depicting their larger political contacts.

97
00:10:08,100 --> 00:10:17,478
That is to say, neither the passengers on United 93 flight nor the policemen in World Trade Center have a grasp on the full picture.

98
00:10:17,780 --> 00:10:24,855
All of a sudden, they find themselves thrown into a terrifying situation, and they have to make the best out of it.

99
00:10:25,740 --> 00:10:31,295
This lack of what Frederic Jameson would have called cognitive mapping is crucial.

100
00:10:32,040 --> 00:10:42,437
Both films depict ordinary people affected by the sudden brutal intrusion of history with a capital H, the invisible real that hurts.

101
00:10:43,100 --> 00:10:45,555
All we see are the disastrous effects.

102
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:48,456
So that in the case of World Trade Center,

103
00:10:49,060 --> 00:10:56,258
One can easily imagine exactly the same film in which the Twin Towers would have collapsed,

104
00:10:56,700 --> 00:11:01,576
not because of the terrorist attack, but due, let us say, to a strong earthquake.

105
00:11:02,020 --> 00:11:05,855
Or even more problematically, we can imagine the same film,

106
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:12,297
the same narrative at least, taking place, for example, to be really evil in a big German city

107
00:11:12,780 --> 00:11:17,178
in the winter of 1944 after a devastating Allied bombing.

108
00:11:17,860 --> 00:11:30,638
Or even more evil surmise, what about the same film taking place in a bombed high-rise building in southern Beirut during the last Lebanon-Israel conflict?

109
00:11:31,261 --> 00:11:32,195
And that's the point.

110
00:11:32,541 --> 00:11:33,875
It cannot take place there.

111
00:11:34,461 --> 00:11:43,253
Such a film taking place in southern Beirut would have been immediately dismissed as a subtle pro-Hezbollah terrorist propaganda or something similar.

112
00:11:43,720 --> 00:11:53,794
What this means is that the two films message ideological, political message, resides in their very abstention from delivering a message.

113
00:11:54,620 --> 00:12:01,258
This abstention is sustained by an implicit trust into one's government.

114
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:05,679
When the enemy attacks, one just don't think, do your duty.

115
00:12:06,060 --> 00:12:11,580
This is what I call Britney Spears' theory of action.

116
00:12:11,740 --> 00:12:19,219
Because effectively, I remember two years ago, seeing Britney Spears' interview on MTV, She was asked, what does she think about Iraq and so on?

117
00:12:19,340 --> 00:12:21,539
And she said, I don't quite understand it.

118
00:12:21,760 --> 00:12:28,096
All I know is that at a certain point, we ordinary people should simply trust our president.

119
00:12:29,080 --> 00:12:39,255
This brings us back to our starting point, to the concrete character of the two films depicting ordinary people in a terse realistic mode.

120
00:12:40,100 --> 00:12:49,177
Now, we philosophers know Kegel's counter-intuitive use of the opposition of abstract and concrete.

121
00:12:49,700 --> 00:13:00,938
As you all know in our ordinary language, abstract are general notions, as opposed to concrete, really existing singular objects and events.

122
00:13:01,441 --> 00:13:03,038
Talking does not exist.

123
00:13:03,381 --> 00:13:07,334
I, maybe, I'm not so sure, exist here now talking to you.

124
00:13:09,321 --> 00:13:14,316
For Hegel, on the contrary, it is such immediate reality which is abstract.

125
00:13:14,640 --> 00:13:22,618
And to render it concrete means to deploy the complex universal context that gives meaning to it.

126
00:13:23,020 --> 00:13:25,952
Let me give you an example which is fictional because I don't smoke.

127
00:13:26,700 --> 00:13:39,076
If I were to smoke here for Hegel, the most abstract approach would have been simply to present me here as this really existing individual smoking.

128
00:13:39,481 --> 00:13:54,276
A concrete approach would have been to render visible, to articulate the complex historical, social, economic, ideological context which has to be here so that I can smoke here.

129
00:13:55,400 --> 00:14:01,277
European colonization of Latin America where, if I am correctly informed, smoking comes

130
00:14:02,560 --> 00:14:14,818
from then the development of industry, plantations, or in a more delicate way, why do we have have to smoke, stress of work, relaxation and so on.

131
00:14:15,140 --> 00:14:30,218
All this context has to be here so that this pseudo-concrete reality can happen and that wider context, this is what we call dialectical mediation, is what for Hegel is concrete.

132
00:14:31,160 --> 00:14:33,676
And back to the two films, here is the problem.

133
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:37,195
Both are abstract in the Hegelian sense.

134
00:14:38,200 --> 00:14:51,078
The function of their down-to-earth depiction of concrete individuals struggling for life is not just to avoid cheap commercial spectacle, but to obliterate the historical context.

135
00:14:51,700 --> 00:15:04,237
Here then is where we are five years later, still unable to locate September 11 into a large narrative, to provide some kind of generally acceptable cognitive mapping.

136
00:15:05,340 --> 00:15:06,683
The third feature.

137
00:15:06,683 --> 00:15:14,424
