01:02:10,941 --> 01:02:13,456
the friendship is saved in this way, frankly, no?

647
01:02:14,160 --> 01:02:25,826
So what I'm saying here is that the most delicate texture of our human relations moves, operates at this level,

648
01:02:25,850 --> 01:02:39,750
at the level not of explicit rules but of this between the lines rules, you know, like I give you an offer but these meta rules tell me it's an offer to be rejected or whatever.

649
01:02:39,802 --> 01:02:44,396
And now I come to the concluding point, if you allow me a little bit of time.

650
01:02:45,880 --> 01:02:53,399
It is that I claim that what is going on today, what worries me, is that these unspoken rules,

651
01:02:53,800 --> 01:03:13,895
what I would call following Hegel, the ethical substance of our being, this I claim is slowly surely, if you want, is disintegrating today.

652
01:03:15,980 --> 01:03:20,098
There are some profound changes operating at that level.

653
01:03:20,680 --> 01:03:21,291
What do you mean by this?

654
01:03:21,760 --> 01:03:25,018
Let me take a book which I, as an atheist, should like, but I'm not.

655
01:03:25,100 --> 01:03:26,172
I think it's a horrible book.

656
01:03:26,981 --> 01:03:30,318
It was a big New York Times bestseller around a year ago,

657
01:03:30,761 --> 01:03:33,237
Sam Harris, The End of Belief.

658
01:03:33,841 --> 01:03:35,100
It tells all the title.

659
01:03:35,181 --> 01:03:43,920
The thesis of the book is our, and he It means specifically our religions of the book, Jewish, Christian, Muslim, and so on.

660
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:46,216
Beliefs are ridiculously out of date.

661
01:03:46,820 --> 01:03:48,938
They belong to a totally different epoch.

662
01:03:49,280 --> 01:03:52,258
