01:08:07,100 --> 01:08:08,572
They thought they are in India, no?

716
01:08:09,560 --> 01:08:13,239
But did you notice how these politically great guys,

717
01:08:13,621 --> 01:08:27,278
if you hear them talk about Native Americans, it's, you know, people who live in a holistic way, harmony with nature, have their dances spiritually connected to Earth, nothing about torture, family rapes, whatever.

718
01:08:27,800 --> 01:08:35,979
And I don't say this in, I think, so what I want to say is that this is for me, this cleansing of the other is the most racist thing.

719
01:08:36,240 --> 01:08:40,035
So back to this, this is the first problem I have with Sam Harris.

720
01:08:40,400 --> 01:08:44,778
The second problem, but it's just a minor remark, is that, fine, so we are following KGB.

721
01:08:45,120 --> 01:08:52,278
Namely, I learned in a book about the misuses of psychiatry in Soviet Union that they already had it.

722
01:08:52,600 --> 01:09:02,579
The standard way to torture dissidents there was under the mask up, because there in Soviet Union in the last decades, dissidents being critical of the system

723
01:09:02,860 --> 01:09:09,357
was defined as a special form of social schizophrenia or whatever, no megalomania that you can create.

724
01:09:09,960 --> 01:09:16,799
They injected something here in the region of your heart, and it was a terrifying experience.

725
01:09:16,960 --> 01:09:19,138
It slowed down your heartbeat.

726
01:09:19,400 --> 01:09:21,154
You thought, like, you know, you are slowly dying.

727
01:09:22,040 --> 01:09:24,019
From the outside, you just took a nap.

728
01:09:24,120 --> 01:09:26,017
It's exactly what Sam Harris described.

729
01:09:26,400 --> 01:09:28,078
From the inside, it was a nightmare.

730
01:09:28,360 --> 01:09:31,374
But, but, now I come to the truly central point.

731
01:09:32,620 --> 01:09:34,959
Nonetheless, you will say, but what's the point?

732
01:09:35,200 --> 01:09:37,855
What is fundamentally wrong with Harris?

733
01:09:38,720 --> 01:09:49,817
Here we come to the topic of what in Judeo-Christian tradition, and Freud also refers to this tradition in his theory of how we relate to others, we call the neighbor.

734
01:09:50,440 --> 01:09:54,556
The neighbor is something very radical in Judeo-Christian tradition.

735
01:09:54,920 --> 01:09:57,877
The neighbor is not the other who is like us.

736
01:09:58,480 --> 01:10:01,479
The neighbor is some kind of a traumatic presence.

737
01:10:01,620 --> 01:10:07,537
It's the other person, if you want, in the abyss of its infinity.

738
01:10:08,060 --> 01:10:10,657
And there is always something monstrous about it.

739
01:10:11,200 --> 01:10:13,879
But the name of that monstrosity is freedom, no?

740
01:10:14,080 --> 01:10:17,756
You cannot ever be sure you promised me this, but how do I know?

741
01:10:18,040 --> 01:10:21,119
How do I know that I can trust you, and so on?

742
01:10:21,280 --> 01:10:24,973
Which is why we need promises with people which are not neighbors.

743
01:10:25,620 --> 01:10:35,138
If I were to know you totally, in a kind of a cognitivist or brain sciences dream, that I know the mechanisms, how you decide, I wouldn't need promises.

744
01:10:35,420 --> 01:10:40,934
Promises are here because precisely I don't know what an abyss you are.

745
01:10:42,160 --> 01:10:51,298
And I think we should be very careful here not to, how should I put it, not to idealize the notion of the neighbor.

746
01:10:51,620 --> 01:10:58,338
There is something irreducibly traumatic in the notion of the neighbor, which is why a little lesson in theology.

747
01:10:59,800 --> 01:11:06,558
If you look already at the Old Testament, I claim that the true function of the 10 commandments

748
01:11:07,682 --> 01:11:15,199
It's not so much to enable you to love your neighbor, but also to keep a neighbor at the proper distance.

749
01:11:15,461 --> 01:11:19,878
It can be very unpleasant, intrusive to come too close to it.

750
01:11:20,360 --> 01:11:20,442
Why?

751
01:11:21,360 --> 01:11:22,340
Let me give you a simple example.

752
01:11:22,400 --> 01:11:26,877
I hope you were, but it's not as loving as it may appear.

753
01:11:27,640 --> 01:11:35,356
You were, some of you at least, I hope most of you all, in a situation where somebody declared intense love to you.

754
01:11:36,140 --> 01:11:42,059
approaches you and you see that it's sincere, it's not a joke, you are the center of my life, I totally love you,

755
01:11:42,083 --> 01:11:49,483
admit it if you are honest that maybe you enjoyed it but for a split of a second at least you were horrified.

756
01:11:49,540 --> 01:12:03,859
I mean it's something horrifying to be in such an intense way the focus of all desires of another person, which is why, do you know that William Butler Yeats famous poem like

757
01:12:04,260 --> 01:12:08,656
You walk, be careful how you walk because you are walking in my dreams.

758
01:12:09,120 --> 01:12:18,100
It's horrible to be somebody who as a real person walks in a dream of dreams of another person.

759
01:12:18,180 --> 01:12:21,158
It's a very claustrophobic experience.

760
01:12:21,580 --> 01:12:27,838
So again, this topic of neighbor is crucial, abyssal topic.

761
01:12:27,940 --> 01:12:35,899
I even claim that we are basically, Our basic fear is fear of the neighbor.

762
01:12:36,060 --> 01:12:40,799
And all racisms play upon this, this abyss of the other.

763
01:12:41,040 --> 01:12:48,875
And that's, incidentally, one of the sad things, for me at least, going on today, namely the fact of how,

764
01:12:50,200 --> 01:12:57,497
did you notice how in the last two, three decades, our politics is defined by two, three features?

765
01:12:58,200 --> 01:13:10,753
One is that the only way to mobilize people, not just to do this technocratic administration, but to mobilize people passionately, is to play on a fear.

766
01:13:11,560 --> 01:13:15,258
The only politics of passions today is a politics of fear.

767
01:13:15,640 --> 01:13:18,538
And unfortunately, not only for the right, also for the left,

768
01:13:18,820 --> 01:13:27,617
fear of immigrants, fear of, I don't know, fear of ecological catastrophe, fear of the state high taxes, whatever you want, fear of sexual depravity, and so on.

769
01:13:28,180 --> 01:13:33,434
I claim what is beneath this is effectively fear of the neighbor.

770
01:13:35,840 --> 01:13:42,695
Another thing to be noted here is how sad thing about today is then how do we deal with the neighbor?

771
01:13:43,260 --> 01:13:47,599
You cannot simply swallow him or her.

772
01:13:47,840 --> 01:13:56,999
Neighbor is out there in its abyss, which is why, again, I claim that this notion of love thy neighbor, it's something very radical.

773
01:13:57,160 --> 01:14:01,959
It means love thy neighbor, love this radical otherness.

774
01:14:02,300 --> 01:14:04,511
Not just love somebody who is like me.

775
01:14:06,360 --> 01:14:11,000
It's that today, the way we deal with it is tolerance.

