793
01:15:53,820 --> 01:15:56,335
So OK, that's another story.

794
01:15:57,201 --> 01:16:03,019
What's underlying this is something that should be called culturalization of politics.

795
01:16:03,360 --> 01:16:11,252
In our postmodern era, where economy is more and more reduced to something that experts do, just administration.

796
01:16:11,920 --> 01:16:18,240
The only conflicts that remain are perceived as conflicts of culture.

797
01:16:18,320 --> 01:16:26,079
But now, really, sorry to conclude, this notion of neighbor is something terrifying, I claim.

798
01:16:26,381 --> 01:16:26,970
In what sense?

799
01:16:27,640 --> 01:16:36,858
In the sense that, again, neighbor is not the wealth of another person, as we put it, his or her inner life, what I see in you.

800
01:16:37,360 --> 01:16:40,376
No, this level is usually a lie.

801
01:16:41,220 --> 01:16:44,355
There is a wonderful poetic, but I totally reject it.

802
01:16:45,400 --> 01:16:47,718
Multicultural phrase, which is something like this.

803
01:16:48,021 --> 01:16:49,499
It's supposed to be a deep insight.

804
01:16:49,600 --> 01:16:51,894
I think it's precisely pseudo-depth.

805
01:16:52,940 --> 01:16:57,059
It's an enemy is someone whose story you have not heard.

806
01:16:57,361 --> 01:17:01,799
It sounds so noble, you know, like you are my enemy if I just objectivize you, you there.

807
01:17:01,920 --> 01:17:10,519
But oh, if I take care or make the effort of understanding you from within, oh, then I will see that you have your standpoint.

808
01:17:10,700 --> 01:17:13,880
OK, up to a certain level, this is undoubtedly true.

809
01:17:14,021 --> 01:17:15,797
But I claim only up to a certain level.

810
01:17:16,200 --> 01:17:22,197
And the limits are clear if I simply paraphrase this or apply to a very specific case.

811
01:17:22,640 --> 01:17:28,360
Would you also be ready to say Hitler was our enemy because we didn't hear his story?

812
01:17:31,314 --> 01:17:32,480
I did hear his story.

813
01:17:32,560 --> 01:17:34,056
I read Mein Kampf and so on.

814
01:17:34,480 --> 01:17:46,798
And what shocks me is how no matter how horrible your politics is, you always can find a nice way, as we usually put it, to rationalize it, to tell yourself a story about it.

815
01:17:47,200 --> 01:17:56,037
So the radical conclusion here is that, and I think this is another deepest insight of Judeo-Christian tradition,

816
01:17:56,540 --> 01:18:02,876
is that the ultimate truth, the truth of you as a unique person, where you really stand,

817
01:18:03,500 --> 01:18:10,038
is not when you go deep into yourself and the deepest sincere self-identification or whatever.

818
01:18:10,401 --> 01:18:12,378
At that level, we usually lie.

819
01:18:12,660 --> 01:18:14,112
That's not the ultimate truth.

820
01:18:15,060 --> 01:18:21,356
Which is why, if you want to get this point, I advise you to read two books.

821
01:18:22,441 --> 01:18:26,359
One is Aldous Huxley, the English guy, gray eminence.

822
01:18:26,600 --> 01:18:34,997
It's the story of Father Joseph, Per Joseph, the foreign minister of Cardinal Richelieu in the early 17th century, the 30 years' war.

823
01:18:35,640 --> 01:18:37,258
What's so fascinating in this person?

824
01:18:37,500 --> 01:18:39,898
He was, for that epoch, evil incarnated.

825
